{"pageProps":{"global":{"id":1,"attributes":{"siteName":"Silky Truth","createdAt":"2025-05-15T23:23:43.879Z","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T03:37:38.146Z","defaultSeo":{"id":2,"metaTitle":"The photographical musings of Nikita Kozlov","metaDescription":"What if the truth didn’t hurt—after all, the truth is all there is, and yet the world remains a beautiful place if you choose to see it that way, silky in its refinement yet truthful enough to be uncomfortable.\n\nSilky light drapes the world in delicate, exotic threads, luxurious to the eye yet secretly strong, so smooth and lustrous that even the hard edges of truth begin to soften. In that glimmer, the genuine and authentic emerge. An irreplaceable shimmer that feels soothing on the surface yet substantive at its core, ultimately liberating us to see beauty without closing our eyes."},"favicon":{"data":null}}},"article":{"id":22,"attributes":{"title":"Neskowin Ghost Raven","description":"The remains of a 2000 year old Sitka Spruce forest located on the beach of Neskowin, Oregon.","content":"Ravens (Corvus corax) belong to the widely distributed family of birds called Corvidae, which also includes crows, magpies, and jays. They are considered to be among the world’s most intelligent animals.\n\nOne common measure of cognitive abilities is called the encephalization quotient, a measure of the relative size of the brain of a particular species compared with the expected value for members of the group to which it belongs. Ravens have relative brain sizes equivalent to non-human primates, such as chimpanzees.\n\nCorvids have been shown to exhibit many interesting behaviors indicating their intelligence. Here are some of my favorite examples:\n\n- Episodic memory: distinguishing between perishable and non-perishable food by observing it decay at different rates and how it should be stored.\n- Theory of Mind: re-caching food in new sites only when they had been observed by others during caching in the first place. Birds that have no experience of stolen caches did not move them, effectively being able to simulate another’s point of view.\n- Self-awareness: Magpies were marked and shown a mirror, and they would work to remove the mark from their body. This is the first evidence of self-directed behavior in a non-mammal.","slug":"neskowin-ghost-raven","createdAt":"2025-06-12T19:56:11.608Z","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T11:25:17.573Z","publishedAt":"2025-06-19T11:25:17.566Z","listed":false,"image":{"data":{"id":496,"attributes":{"url":"https://photography-blog-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536.JPG","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1080,"height":1350,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".JPG","url":"https://photography-blog-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/large_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536.JPG","hash":"large_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"large_la_vida_bokeh-2.JPG","path":null,"size":69.58,"width":800,"height":1000},"small":{"ext":".JPG","url":"https://photography-blog-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/small_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536.JPG","hash":"small_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"small_la_vida_bokeh-2.JPG","path":null,"size":20.93,"width":400,"height":500},"medium":{"ext":".JPG","url":"https://photography-blog-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/medium_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536.JPG","hash":"medium_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"medium_la_vida_bokeh-2.JPG","path":null,"size":41.89,"width":600,"height":750},"thumbnail":{"ext":".JPG","url":"https://photography-blog-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/thumbnail_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536.JPG","hash":"thumbnail_la_vida_bokeh_2_a3dd19d536","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"thumbnail_la_vida_bokeh-2.JPG","path":null,"size":3.14,"width":125,"height":156}},"provider_metadata":null}}},"gallery":{"id":23,"caption":"Gallery for Neskowin Ghost Raven","gallery_items":[{"id":456,"caption":"la_vida_bokeh-6.JPG","alt_text":"la_vida_bokeh-6.JPG","display_size":"medium"